      "heading": "Bayes' rule: how evidence updates belief",
      "narration": "Bayes' rule flips the conditioning direction, and it is derived in one line from the two equal ways of writing the joint of H and E. The result: P of H-given-E equals P of E-given-H, times P of H, divided by P of E. Say it in named pieces: the posterior equals the likelihood times the prior, divided by the evidence. In words, your belief in hypothesis H after seeing evidence E equals how well H explains E, times how plausible H was beforehand, all renormalized. Those three names — prior for P of H, likelihood for P of E-given-H, and posterior for P of H-given-E — are permanent vocabulary; you will hear the word prior in every ML conversation you ever have. And Bayes guards against a famous trap, the base-rate fallacy, which deserves a full worked example. A disease affects one percent of patients. A test catches ninety percent of true cases, its sensitivity, but also false-alarms on nine percent of healthy patients. You test positive. What is the chance you are actually sick? Run Bayes: nine-tenths times one-hundredth, on top, divided by nine-tenths times one-hundredth plus nine-hundredths times ninety-nine-hundredths — that is nought-point-zero-zero-nine over nought-point-zero-nine-eight-one, which is about nine-point-two percent. Not ninety percent — nine. Picture ten thousand patients: ninety of them are truly sick and test positive, but eight hundred ninety-one healthy ones also test positive, so your ninety true positives drown under the false alarms. Most people, including doctors in published studies, guess eighty to ninety percent, and they are wrong because the prior is doing the work: rare things stay improbable even after moderately strong evidence. This is exactly why fraud-detection and medical-AI systems produce mostly false positives on rare classes unless the model is extremely precise, and it connects directly to precision and recall in Part Two. Bayes is the arithmetic of not fooling yourself when the base rate is low.",
