      "heading": "Expectation and variance: the summary numbers",
      "narration": "Two summary numbers compress a whole distribution. The expectation, E of X, is the sum over x of x times the probability of X equals x — the probability-weighted average. The variance, Var of X, is the expected value of the squared deviation from the mean, E of the quantity X-minus-E-of-X, squared, and its square root sigma is the standard deviation. Expectation is the long-run average per trial: a fair die has expectation one-plus-two-up-to-six over six, which is three-point-five — a value never actually rolled, but always approached as you average more and more rolls. Variance just measures how spread out the outcomes are around that average. The lottery makes expectation concrete as a decision tool. The Friends gang pools money for Powerball, and Phoebe insists the vibes are right, but run the numbers: a ticket costs one dollar, the jackpot is three hundred million, and the odds are about one in two hundred ninety-two million, so the expected winnings are three hundred million times one-over-two-hundred-ninety-two-million, about one dollar three cents before taxes and shared jackpots drag the realistic return to roughly fifty cents per dollar ticket. Expectation does not say you will not win — someone does — it says the probability-weighted average outcome is a loss, every ticket turning a dollar into fifty cents on average, forever. Now why machine learning cares, concretely and deeply: every loss you minimize is an expectation — the average wrongness over the data distribution — which you estimate by averaging over a batch of examples. And here is the statistical license for the whole training procedure: stochastic gradient descent works because a random mini-batch's average gradient is an unbiased estimate of the true full-data gradient, meaning its expectation equals the true gradient, with a variance that shrinks as the batch grows. That is the entire justification for training on batches of thirty-two examples instead of the whole internet at every step — the batch gradient is noisy but centered on the right answer, and bigger batches just reduce the noise. Casinos, insurance, loss functions, and the expected-reward objective of RLHF in Part Six all live on this one formula: the probability-weighted average, computed before the dice roll.",
